erspectives on figures such as Plato, Aristotle, Adam Smith, William James, Rachel Carson, Maurice Merleau-Ponty, Jean-Paul Sartre, and Abraham Heschel. Along the way, she explains how these singular emotions empower us to be open-minded, to experience joy and hope, and to be resilient in the face of personal troubles and global challenges.Taking inspiration from Descartes’s portrayal of wonder as “that sudden surprise of the soul,” this illuminating book reveals how wonder and awe are catalysts that can help us reclaim what makes life worth living and preserve the things we find wonderful and valuable in our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aWonder (Philosophy) 0aWonder (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aAbraham Heschel science fiction.  aDescartes.  aHelen De Cruz.  aImmanuel Kant.  aMerleau-Ponty.  aRachel Carson.  aSartre.  aWonderstruck: How Wonder and Awe Shape the Way We Think.  aZen Buddhism.  aastronomy.  aawe.  acuriosity cabinets.  aearly modern philosophy.  aemotions.  amagic.  areligion.  ascience.  athe scientific revolution.  awonder.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691232171?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691232171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691232171/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles